static cast vs dynamic cast

- use static_cast only if you are 100% sure the cast is good.
• use dynamic_cast if you are not sure. 

// how dynamic cast works:
  
A* 	dyn_a 	= 	dynamic_cast<A*>(p);  
	// dynamic_cast checks 'p' to make sure it points to an 'A'
     	// Let us say it does, so this cast is safe.  dynamic_cast succeeds.


B* dyn_b = dynamic_cast<B*>(p);  
	// dynamic_cast checks 'p'.  
	//Let us say that 'p' does not point to a 'B', 
    	//so this is a bad cast.  
	//dynamic_cast will fail and dyn_b will be == nullptr

// how static_cast works
 
A* sta_a = static_cast<A*>(p);  
	// static_cast assumes the cast is good.  
	//No runtime check
  	// sta_a will be identical to dyn_a above

B* sta_b = static_cast<B*>(p);  
	// static_cast assumes the cast is good... BUT IT ISN'T
    	//  'p' does not point to a 'B', so this is a bad cast!  static_cast succeeds, resulting in
    	//  'sta_b' being a BAD POINTER.  Dereferencing sta_b has undefined behavior.


